.. _iris_dataset:

Iris plants dataset
--------------------

**Data Set Characteristics:**

    :Number of Instances: 150 (50 in each of three classes)
    :Number of Attributes: 4 numeric, predictive attributes and the class
    :Attribute Information:
        - sepal length in cm
        - sepal width in cm
        - petal length in cm
        - petal width in cm
        - class:
                - Iris-Setosa
                - Iris-Versicolour
                - Iris-Virginica
                
    :Summary Statistics:

    ============== ==== ==== ======= ===== ====================
                    Min  Max   Mean    SD   Class Correlation
    ============== ==== ==== ======= ===== ====================
    sepal length:   4.3  7.9   5.84   0.83    0.7826
    sepal width:    2.0  4.4   3.05   0.43   -0.4194
    petal length:   1.0  6.9   3.76   1.76    0.9490  (high!)
    petal width:    0.1  2.5   1.20   0.76    0.9565  (high!)
    ============== ==== ==== ======= ===== ====================

    :Missing Attribute Values: None
    :Class Distribution: 33.3% for each of 3 classes.
    :Creator: R.A. Fisher
    :Donor: Michael Marshall (MARSHALL%PLU@io.arc.nasa.gov)
    :Date: July, 1988

The famous Iris database, first used by Sir R.A. Fisher. The dataset is taken
from Fisher's paper. Note that it's the same as in R, but not as in the UCI
Machine Learning Repository, which has two wrong data points.

This is perhaps the best known database to be found in the
pattern recognition literature.  Fisher's paper is a classic in the field and
is referenced frequently to this day.  (See Duda & Hart, for example.)  The
data set contains 3 classes of 50 instances each, where each class refers to a
type of iris plant.  One class is linearly separable from the other 2; the
latter are NOT linearly separable from each other.

.. topic:: References

   - Fisher, R.A. "The use of multiple measurements in taxonomic problems"
     Annual Eugenics, 7, Part II, 179-188 (1936); also in "Contributions to
     Mathematical Statistics" (John Wiley, NY, 1950).
   - Duda, R.O., & Hart, P.E. (1973) Pattern Classification and Scene Analysis.
     (Q327.D83) John Wiley & Sons.  ISBN 0-471-22361-1.  See page 218.
   - Dasarathy, B.V. (1980) "Nosing Around the Neighborhood: A New System
     Structure and Classification Rule for Recognition in Partially Exposed
     Environments".  IEEE Transactions on Pattern Analysis and Machine
     Intelligence, Vol. PAMI-2, No. 1, 67-71.
   - Gates, G.W. (1972) "The Reduced Nearest Neighbor Rule".  IEEE Transactions
     on Information Theory, May 1972, 431-433.
   - See also: 1988 MLC Proceedings, 54-64.  Cheeseman et al"s AUTOCLASS II
     conceptual clustering system finds 3 classes in the data.
   - Many, many more ...
In [14]:
from sklearn import cluster
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
import numpy as np
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error

centers = []
labels = []
inertia = []
ks = np.arange(20)
for k in ks:
    if k == 0:
        continue
    kmeans_clf = cluster.KMeans(n_clusters=k, max_iter=1000, random_state = 42)
    kmeans_clf.fit(X)
    #print(kmeans_clf.cluster_centers_)
    #print(kmeans_clf.labels_)
    labels.append(kmeans_clf.labels_)
    centers.append(kmeans_clf.cluster_centers_)
    inertia.append(kmeans_clf.inertia_ / 150)
labels = np.array(labels)
acc = []
for label in labels:
    acc.append(accuracy_score(y_true = y, y_pred = label))

plt.figure(figsize = (20, 10))
plt.plot(ks[1:], acc, 'o-')
plt.grid('on')
plt.title('Validation Accuracy vs. k', fontsize = 20)
plt.xlabel('k', fontsize = 15)
plt.ylabel('Accuracy', fontsize = 15)
plt.show()

plt.grid('on')

plt.xlabel('# of clusters', fontsize = 15)
plt.ylabel('MSE', fontsize = 15)

In [16]:
from sklearn import decomposition

kmeans_clf = cluster.KMeans(n_clusters=4, max_iter=1000, random_state = 42)
kmeans_clf.fit(X)
y_kmeans = kmeans_clf.predict(X)
plt.figure(figsize = (20, 10))
plt.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=y_kmeans, s=50, cmap='viridis')

centers = kmeans_clf.cluster_centers_
plt.scatter(centers[:, 0], centers[:, 1], c='black', s=200, alpha=0.5)
plt.title('Kmeans Clustering Visualization', fontsize = 20)
plt.show()

The best number of clusters is 2, since it has the highest accuracy score. By broadly looking at the plot above, we can see that starting from # of clusteres = 1, the accuracy score has a general trend to decrease with increasing # of clusters.¶

However, this is a unsupervised learning problem, which means we should ignore accuracy because in real life we would have that for reference. Hence, for the final implementation of kmeans clustering, I choose the number of clusters of 4 because based on the mse of the data fit vs. # of clusters above, the turning point of the trending seems to occur around 4.¶

#visualizing components' explained variance

from mpl_toolkits.axes_grid1 import make_axes_locatable
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn import decomposition

n_components = 40
pca=decomposition.PCA(n_components=n_components)
pca.fit(X)
pca.explained_variance_ratio_

plt.figure(figsize=(30,15))
plt.plot(np.arange(1,41),pca.explained_variance_ratio_[:40],linestyle='--',color='green',lw=5,ms=8,label='Individual')
plt.plot(np.arange(1,41),np.cumsum(pca.explained_variance_ratio_[:40]),marker='o',color='b',linestyle='--',lw=5,ms=8, label='Cumulative')
plt.axhline(y=0.95, color='r', linestyle='-')
plt.text(0.5, 0.9, '95% cut-off threshold', color = 'red', fontsize=20)
plt.legend(fontsize = 25)
plt.xlabel('Component #', fontsize = 25)
plt.ylabel('% Variance Explained', fontsize = 25)
plt.xticks(size =20)
plt.yticks(size =20)
plt.grid(axis='x')
plt.show()
In [23]:
#visualizing reconstruction loss

losses = []
components = np.arange(1, 41)
for n_components in components:
    pca=decomposition.PCA(n_components=n_components)
    X_re = pca.fit_transform(X)
    proj = pca.inverse_transform(X_re)
    loss = ((X - proj) ** 2).mean()
    losses.append(loss)
losses = np.array(losses)

plt.figure(figsize = (20, 10))
plt.plot(components, losses, 'o-', color='b')
plt.xlabel('Component #', fontsize = 20)
plt.ylabel('Reconstruction error', fontsize = 20)
plt.xticks(size =15)
plt.yticks(size =15)
plt.grid('on')
plt.show()

In [29]:
#Strategy1: Tuning parameters based on rule of thumb

from sklearn import decomposition
from sklearn import pipeline
from sklearn import svm
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
import numpy as np
from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedShuffleSplit

n_components = 150
C = [0.0001, 0.005, 0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 5, 10, 100]
gamma = [0.001, 0.005, 0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 1]

pca=decomposition.PCA(n_components = n_components)
reg=svm.SVC(kernel='rbf')
pipe = pipeline.Pipeline([('pca',pca), ('reg',reg)])
#reg.get_params().keys()
cv = StratifiedShuffleSplit(n_splits=5, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)
estimator_acc = GridSearchCV(pipe,
                         dict(reg__C=C,
                              reg__gamma=gamma), cv=cv, scoring = 'accuracy')
estimator_f1 = GridSearchCV(pipe,
                         dict(reg__C=C,
                              reg__gamma=gamma), cv=cv, scoring = 'f1_micro')
estimator_roc_auc = GridSearchCV(pipe,
                         dict(reg__C=C,
                              reg__gamma=gamma), cv=cv, scoring = 'roc_auc')

estimator_acc.fit(X_re, y)
print("The best parameters are %s with a score of %0.2f with accuracy_score"
      % (estimator_acc.best_params_, estimator_acc.best_score_))
estimator_f1.fit(X_re, y)
print("The best parameters are %s with a score of %0.2f with f1_score"
      % (estimator_f1.best_params_, estimator_f1.best_score_))
estimator_roc_auc.fit(X_re, y)
print("The best parameters are %s with a score of %0.2f with roc_auc"
      % (estimator_roc_auc.best_params_, estimator_roc_auc.best_score_))

The best parameters are {'reg__C': 1, 'reg__gamma': 0.005} with a score of 0.72 with accuracy_score
The best parameters are {'reg__C': 1, 'reg__gamma': 0.005} with a score of 0.72 with f1_score
The best parameters are {'reg__C': 0.0001, 'reg__gamma': 0.01} with a score of 0.76 with roc_auc

Based on rule of thumb, we take # of components to be 150, and tune the other two parameters, the result is shown above.¶

#Strategy2: Tuning three parameters all at once

n_components = [10, 50, 110, 120, 130, 135, 140, 145, 150, 155, 160, 170]
C = [0.0001, 0.005, 0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 5, 10, 100]
gamma = [0.001, 0.005, 0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 1]

pca=decomposition.PCA()
reg=svm.SVC(kernel='rbf')
pipe = pipeline.Pipeline([('pca',pca), ('reg',reg)])
#reg.get_params().keys()
cv = StratifiedShuffleSplit(n_splits=5, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)
estimator_acc = GridSearchCV(pipe,
                         dict(pca__n_components=n_components,
                              reg__C=C,
                              reg__gamma=gamma), cv=cv, scoring = 'accuracy')
estimator_f1 = GridSearchCV(pipe,
                         dict(pca__n_components=n_components,
                              reg__C=C,
                              reg__gamma=gamma), cv=cv, scoring = 'f1_micro')
estimator_roc_auc = GridSearchCV(pipe,
                         dict(pca__n_components=n_components,
                              reg__C=C,
                              reg__gamma=gamma), cv=cv, scoring = 'roc_auc')

estimator_acc.fit(X_re, y)
print("The best parameters are %s with a score of %0.2f with accuracy_score"
      % (estimator_acc.best_params_, estimator_acc.best_score_))
estimator_f1.fit(X_re, y)
print("The best parameters are %s with a score of %0.2f with f1_score"
      % (estimator_f1.best_params_, estimator_f1.best_score_))
estimator_roc_auc.fit(X_re, y)
print("The best parameters are %s with a score of %0.2f with roc_auc"
      % (estimator_roc_auc.best_params_, estimator_roc_auc.best_score_))

The best parameters are {'pca__n_components': 150, 'reg__C': 1, 'reg__gamma': 0.005} with a score of 0.72 with accuracy_score
The best parameters are {'pca__n_components': 150, 'reg__C': 1, 'reg__gamma': 0.005} with a score of 0.72 with f1_score
The best parameters are {'pca__n_components': 110, 'reg__C': 1, 'reg__gamma': 0.005} with a score of 0.77 with roc_auc

No based on rule of thumb, tune all three parameters at once. Based on the computations shown above, we see that there are only slight difference between the scores computed based on f1, accuracy and roc_auc scoring metrics.¶

We could draw the assumption that if we predict in terms of AUC on the blind data, the prediction score would be around 0.77 or 77%.¶
